You can also use this word as a noun, then it becomes a collective noun: "De belangstelling van deelnemers aan een cursus was erg divers en interessant." This sentence translates into: "The interest from participants of a course was very diverse and interesting." Here we see again the same structure as before, but now instead of using verbs like 'verbaal', 'onderwijs', etc.. I've replaced those with the noun 'belangstelling'. Belangstellingen translates directly to the plural form of interest. So instead of saying "De beloning van studenten voor hun prestaties op school is zeer divers en afhankelijk van verschillende factoren", I could simply write "De beloning was zeer divers en afhankelijk van verschillende factoren." And if i were to say "Het bezit van materialen om te leren werken met elektriciteit kan sommigen interessanten." Then it would translate into: The possession of materials for learning how to work with electricity may interest some people. With the use of "-en", the original verb "Intrigeren" gets transformed into an infinitive, and thus we get another new verb "interessanten".
